rmk: This clip features calls from Tree Sparrows in Vietnam, cross-referenced with equivalent calls from a House Sparrow in Northern Ireland. Tree Sparrow comes first; after 0:12, it is House Sparrow. Although Tree Sparrow is ubiquitous in eastern Asia, House Sparrows also occur in at least eastern Vietnam. So the 'chirp' of each species can sometimes be heard coming from mixed parties of Tree and House Sparrows. Around Da Nang and Hoi An, Tree Sparrows outnumbered House Sparrows; in most parts, House Sparrows were absent.  Compared to House Sparrow, the 'standard' chirp of Tree Sparrow is harder and monosyllabic. It really is just the word 'chip' uttered in repeated series. House Sparrow's equivalent, although it sounds like a single syllable, is closer to two syllables. I hear it as 'chill-ip'  or 'chleep'. Often there is a slight change in the individual note if you listen to a series. Looking at sonograms of each species' call, the 'clean, abrupt' chip of Tree Sparrow is represented by a single 'blade' (a guillotine shape), whereas House Sparrow's chirp has a layered profile, showing that the sound is stretched over more than one utterance.  In fact, the sonogram of House Sparrow's note looks like a three-piece Venetian blind.

rmk: This common bird’s calls are under-recorded. I saw a pair courting today with the presumed male, excited, with a cocked tail and all hyper-alert towards the female. What was interesting was the vocalisation the bird was making. The bird made these very frequent, regular calls to woo the female. These calls are very unlike the conventional, intermittent ‘chip’ the bird usually makes. These courtship calls have been described as ‘tschip’ by the Thai National Parks, 2019 website (https://www.thainationalparks.com/species/eurasian-tree-sparrow).  In my recording they occurred at 2 calls per second (65 in 30 second recording). Amplified recording here. The recording it starts off with a few conventional ‘chips’ and then launches into a long series of ‘tschips’ (a Black-naped Oriole in the background). There was no response from the female in the time I was allowed to observe them – they flew off together soon after.
